		`

		<description><![CDATA[Things detached from names can be seen, witnessed, / but naming things sates the hunger God’s absence leaves]]></description>
		<content:encoded><![CDATA[<img width="1600" height="1067" src="https://walrus-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/img/POE_ChrisBanks_2023_1800.jpeg" class="webfeedsFeaturedVisual wp-post-image" alt="A photo illustration of a black-and-white headshot of poet Chris Banks. Behind him are two outlines of his silhouette in two different shades of brown against a solid darker brown background." style="display: block; margin-bottom: 5px; clear:both;max-width: 100%;" link_thumbnail="" srcset="https://walrus-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/img/POE_ChrisBanks_2023_1800.jpeg 1600w, https://walrus-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/img/POE_ChrisBanks_2023_1800-735x490.jpeg 735w, https://walrus-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/img/POE_ChrisBanks_2023_1800-1536x1024.jpeg 1536w, https://walrus-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/img/POE_ChrisBanks_2023_1800-1200x800.jpeg 1200w, https://walrus-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/img/POE_ChrisBanks_2023_1800-348x232.jpeg 348w" sizes="(max-width: 1600px) 100vw, 1600px" /><p>I am trying not to lie to you, trying not to say I am a body<br />
that breaks into blossom whenever I see horses, like James<br />
Wright famously wrote. I once believed in the psalmic line,<br />
which is one way to get out of one’s self; alcohol is another.<br />
Some poets use both. I certainly did, until neither worked<br />
anymore. Things detached from names can be seen, witnessed,<br />
but naming things sates the hunger God’s absence leaves. Poetry<br />
is two parts pilgrimage, one part education. The shrines are<br />
different for everyone&mdash;childhood, the past, the Edenic place,<br />
maybe the unthawed snow burying a neighbourhood in 1975.<br />
All of it deserves its share of worship, of praise, despite half<br />
the people sleeping in those houses in 1975 now being extinct.<br />
Even the World War II veteran who sold us pop and chips<br />
out of the back of the Legion. Stan with his one good eye.</p>The post <a href="https://thewalrus.ca/sonnet/">Sonnet</a> first appeared on <a href="https://thewalrus.ca">The Walrus</a>.]]></content:encoded>

		
		
